What is SQL?

SQL is a standard language for accessing and manipulating databases.

SQL stands for Structured Query Language.

SQL lets you access and manipulate databases.

SQL became a standard of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) in 1986, and of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1987.

What Can SQL do?

  • SQL can execute queries against a database (OUR FOCUS).

  • SQL can create new tables in a database.

  • SQL can retrieve data from a database (OUR FOCUS).

  • SQL can insert records in a database.

  • SQL can update records in a database.

  • SQL can delete records from a database.

  • SQL can create new databases.

  • SQL can set permissions on tables, procedures, and views. Procedures and views are outside the scope of this course.

SQL is a Standard - BUTâ¦.

Although SQL is an ANSI/ISO standard, there are different versions of the SQL language (e.g., some syntax are different in Microsoft (MS) SQL vs Oracle SQL).

Today, we will be working with PostGreSQL (often just referred to as Postgres). Postgres, is a free and open-source relational database management system.

However, to be compliant with the ANSI standard, they all support at least the major commands (such as SELECT, UPDATE, DELETE, INSERT, WHERE) in a similar manner.

Command and keywords: Not case sensitive

Keep in mind that SQL keywords (e.g., SELECT, UPDATE, DELETE, INSERT, WHERE) are NOT case sensitive : select is the same as SELECT.

SQL Keywords: Required Order

This will make more sense later but having this above as a reference

SELECT > FROM > WHERE > GROUP BY > HAVING > ORDER BY

Schema and Tables

There are two terminologies that I want you to be vaguely familiar with.

A SQL Schema is formally defined as a collection of database objects. To an extent, you may think of schema as a database folder.

Tables are tabular objects (think of R data frames or excel data) that exist within a schema. When you pull data from a SQL database, you are effectively pulling against/from SQL tables.

When we pull data from SQL, we need to specify an âaddressâ where to pull the table from. This is typically in the following format: [schema_name].[table_name].

For example, if you want to pull data from the rural_development table that lives within the investment schema, the location you want to pull from is investment.rural_development

Intersection of R and SQL

Normally, you use database management tools to access and management databases. For Postgres, pgAdmin 4 is one of the most popular tools to manage and access Postgres databases.

Although I will do a quick demo of pgAdmin 4, I am not requiring its use. If you are interested in downloading it, https://www.pgadmin.org/download/. One benefit of using pgAdmin 4 over R and other programming languages is: you can easily see which schemas and tables exist within your database.

But a key focus of this class is instead connecting and pulling data from our PostGreSQL database using R. The following packages are needed:

# install.packages("odbc")
library(odbc)

# install.packages("DBI")
library(DBI)

# install.packages("RPostgres")
library(RPostgres)

Doing SQL in R

The simplest query you can run in SQL for pulling data is:

SELECT *

FROM [SCHEMA].[TABLE];

SELECT tells SQL the variables you want.

Since the symbol * is placed after SELECT, * tells SQL you are requesting all available variables from the table you indicated.

Please note that semi colon at the end of the SQL Query.

# Place SQL query between the quotation marks
sql_query <- "
SELECT *
FROM penguins.adelie;
"

# This will return the database data or table you requested
dbGetQuery(connection, sql_query)

SQL SELECT

Instead of using *, you can specify variables you are only interested in. You can do so by spelling out the variables you want: separated by commas. See examples below that only requests three specific variables/columns:

# Place SQL query between the quotation marks
sql_query <- "
SELECT species, island, bill_length_mm
FROM penguins.adelie
"

# This will return the database data or table you requested
dbGetQuery(connection, sql_query)

Saving SQL Data as R Data Frame

Quick note: You can save table/data returned by dbGetQuery() into your R environment. You just need to use the assignment operator (<-).

# Place SQL query between the quotation marks
sql_query <- "
SELECT species, island, bill_length_mm
FROM penguins.adelie
"

# This will return the database data or table you requested and save it as adelie_data into your R evn't
adelie_data <- dbGetQuery(connection, sql_query)

head(adelie_data)
  species    island bill_length_mm
1  Adelie Torgersen           39.1
2  Adelie Torgersen           39.5
3  Adelie Torgersen           40.3
4  Adelie Torgersen             NA
5  Adelie Torgersen           36.7
6  Adelie Torgersen           39.3

SQL SELECT DISTINCT

Very similar to distinct from tidyverse which returns unique combinations of variables selected. Hereâs an example for sex and island.

# Place SQL query between the quotation marks
sql_query <- "
SELECT DISTINCT sex
FROM penguins.adelie
"

# This will return the database data or table you requested
dbGetQuery(connection, sql_query)
     sex
1   <NA>
2 female
3   male
# Place SQL query between the quotation marks
sql_query <- "
SELECT DISTINCT sex, island
FROM penguins.adelie
"

# This will return the database data or table you requested
dbGetQuery(connection, sql_query)
     sex    island
1   male     Dream
2 female    Biscoe
3   <NA>     Dream
4   male    Biscoe
5   male Torgersen
6 female Torgersen
7   <NA> Torgersen
8 female     Dream

Resulting data from above is messy (unordered). We will improve this query later on to return ordered data from the data base.

SQL WHERE

Similar to the behavior of filter() where it returns a subset of data that meets your conditions.

One condition: Below is an example of returning data if and only if island is equals to âDreamâ (note the single quotation mark here). Also note that the equal sign is only one equal sign between island and âDreamâ within the script. YOU HAVE TO USE SINGLE QUOTE!!!!

sql_query <- "
SELECT *
FROM penguins.adelie
WHERE island = 'Dream'
"

# This will return the database data or table you requested
dbGetQuery(connection, sql_query)

Multiple conditions: Below is an example of returning data if and only if island is equals to âDreamâ (note the single quotation mark here) and bill_length_mm > 40. You can add as many conditions as long as there is AND between the conditions. OR is also available.

# Additional chunk created in class:
# pt here is you can keep adding AND with the additional condition you want your data table to meet
sql_query <- "
SELECT *
FROM penguins.adelie
WHERE island = 'Dream' AND bill_length_mm > 40 AND bill_depth_mm <= 20
"

Operators compatible with WHERE

Operator Description Example
= Equal WHERE island = âDreamâ
> Greater than WHERE bill_length_mm > 40
< Less than WHERE bill_length_mm < 40
>= Greater than or equal WHERE bill_depth_mm >= 20
<= Less than or equal WHERE bill_depth_mm <= 20
<> Not equal. Note: In some versions of SQL this operator may be written as != WHERE island <> âDreamâ
BETWEEN Between a certain range WHERE bill_depth_mm BETWEEN 10 AND 20
LIKE Search for a pattern (often used with % symbol). With the example to the right, âT%â for example will return results where island starts with letter T. % here is called a wildcard character. Technically, % represents zero or more characters. WHERE island LIKE âT%â
IN To specify multiple possible values for a column WHERE island IN (âDreamâ, âTorgersenâ)

Here is an example of using IN to capture multiple matches for island:

sql_query <- "
SELECT *
FROM penguins.adelie
WHERE island IN ('Dream', 'Torgersen')
"

dbGetQuery(connection, sql_query)

LIMIT: Caution if you have no idea how large your tables are

Typically, when you are exploring new tables and you have no idea how large the tables are, you may want to limit the number of results returned to you by the server to prevent performance issues that could impact your database servers, your computer, or both.

One way to limit your data is to end your SQL query with the LIMIT statement. LIMIT 3 below limits the returned data to three rows only. You may adjust the number after LIMIT of course to meet your needs (e.g., LIMIT 100 to get a 100 sample).

LIMIT works for postgres, but donât necessarily work with other versions of SQL (e.g., Oracle PSSQL).

sql_query <- "
SELECT *
FROM penguins.adelie
LIMIT 3
"

dbGetQuery(connection, sql_query)
  species    island bill_length_mm bill_depth_mm flipper_length_mm body_mass_g
1  Adelie Torgersen           39.1          18.7               181        3750
2  Adelie Torgersen           39.5          17.4               186        3800
3  Adelie Torgersen           40.3          18.0               195        3250
     sex year
1   male 2007
2 female 2007

SQL ORDER BY

The ORDER BY keyword is used to sort the result-set in ascending or descending order. Default is ascending order. Let us modify one of the scripts we ran earlier to order by bill_length_mm in ascending order (alphabetically for text/string data, from least to most for numeric data).

sql_query <- "
SELECT *
FROM penguins.adelie
ORDER BY bill_length_mm 
"
# Note: You may also do ORDER BY bill_length_mm ASC

dbGetQuery(connection, sql_query)

Can you order by two variables? Yes. Separate variables by comma!

sql_query <- "
SELECT *
FROM penguins.adelie
ORDER BY island DESC, bill_length_mm
"

Inherent order in SQL

SELECT is required to be the first line in any basic query followed by FROM. This is the most basic SQL query you may run.

How about adding and combining WHERE and ORDER BY? WHERE needs to come before ORDER BY. If you attempt to put ORDER BY before WHERE, you will get an error.

Hereâs a basic example of combining these four keywords:

sql_query <- "
SELECT *
FROM penguins.adelie
WHERE sex = 'female' AND bill_length_mm > 40
ORDER BY island, bill_length_mm DESC
"
# If you want to be more specific: ORDER BY island ASC, bill_length_mm DESC

dbGetQuery(connection, sql_query)

WHERE and NULL

Null is a fancy term for empty. Equivalent to NAs in R.

Often, you are interested in excluding data whenever the values for a specific variable is empty or null.

Hereâs a basic script that will only return data if and only if body_mass_g is not empty:

sql_query <- "
SELECT *
FROM penguins.adelie
WHERE body_mass_g is NOT NULL
"

dbGetQuery(connection, sql_query)

SQL Aggregating Functions

An aggregate function is a function that performs a calculation on a set of values.

Aggregate functions are often used with the GROUP BY clause of the SELECT statement if you want your statistics to be broken down by groups. The GROUP BY clause splits the result-set into groups of values and the aggregate function can be used to return a single value for each group. (Similar to how group_by() breaks down statistics you may need to computer in R).

The most commonly used SQL aggregate functions are:

  • MIN() - returns the smallest value within the selected column

  • MAX() - returns the largest value within the selected column

  • COUNT() - returns the number of rows in a set

  • SUM() - returns the total sum of a numerical column

  • AVG() - returns the average value of a numerical column

Before we continue, let us revisit the USDA rural development data we have worked with earlier in the semester. This time, it exists as a database tabled named ruraldevelopment that lives within the investment schema. Let us refamiliarize ourselves with the data by printing the first 10 rows:

Calculating overall statistics

The most basic aggregating function you can run is COUNT(*).

COUNT(*) tells you the number of rows available within a table. Very useful for investigating new tables to determine number of data rows available.

sql_query <- "
SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM investment.ruraldevelopment
"

dbGetQuery(connection, sql_query)
  count
1  4169

This time, let us use another aggregating function: SUM(). The example below is an example where we tally the overall sum for total_investment_dollars

sql_query <- "
SELECT SUM(total_investment_dollars)
FROM investment.ruraldevelopment
"

dbGetQuery(connection, sql_query)
           sum
1 377616256839

Again, you can do multiple aggregating functions like in Râs summarize(). Just make sure the functions are separated by a comma. Hereâs an example that calculates both the SUM() and AVG() of total_investment_dollars:

sql_query <- "
SELECT SUM(total_investment_dollars), AVG(total_investment_dollars)
FROM investment.ruraldevelopment
"

dbGetQuery(connection, sql_query) 
           sum      avg
1 377616256839 90577178

Quick detour: aliases

Aliases allows you to rename any variables or aggregates. For the aggregates we just did, you can rename the data returned by affixing AS [new_name]

In the example below, the calculated sum is renamed into total_dollars:

sql_query <- "
SELECT SUM(total_investment_dollars) AS total_dollars
FROM investment.ruraldevelopment
"

dbGetQuery(connection, sql_query)
  total_dollars
1  377616256839

Aggregating with GROUP BY

Again, GROUP BY is simply the same as dplyr/tidyverseâs group_by() in behavior where you are breaking down statistics by some categorical variables.

You specify the GROUP BY categorical variables by appending the variables you want the data broken down by. IMPORTANT NOTE: Since I want to GROUP BY state_name, you need to include state_name as well under SELECT.

sql_query <- "
SELECT state_name, SUM(total_investment_dollars) AS total_dollars
FROM investment.ruraldevelopment
GROUP BY state_name 
"

Combining GROUP BY with WHERE and ORDER BY

Order you need to follow: SELECT > FROM > WHERE > GROUP BY > ORDER BY

The example below uses all five.

sql_query <- "
SELECT state_name, SUM(total_investment_dollars) AS total_dollars
FROM investment.ruraldevelopment
WHERE state_name IN ('Alabama', 'Virginia', 'New Mexico')
GROUP BY state_name 
ORDER BY state_name 
"

dbGetQuery(connection, sql_query)
  state_name total_dollars
1    Alabama   10205762054
2 New Mexico    2624109226
3   Virginia   17451945311

The one quick I want to highlight is how to use NOT IN, which allows you to excluding multiple items at the same time.

The example below uses NOT IN to exclude destination airports (dest): SNA, DEN, IND, HOU, ORF:

sql_query <- "
SELECT *
FROM myschema.flights
WHERE origin = 'EWR' AND dest NOT IN ('SNA', 'DEN', 'IND', 'HOU', 'ORF')
"

dbGetQuery(connection, sql_query)

HAVING: Refining results from group by

When you are using order by, it creates some form of tally (e.g., count(*), sum(ofsomething)) broken by groups. Here is an example where we tabulated the total investment dollars for each state:

sql_query <- "
SELECT state_name, SUM(total_investment_dollars) AS total_dollars
FROM investment.ruraldevelopment
GROUP BY state_name 
"

dbGetQuery(connection, sql_query)

Suppose we are interested in only keeping the states where the total federal investment dollars is at least 10000000000 (10 billion). Since we are aggregating via group by, we have to use HAVING to only keep a subset of the group by tally.

Having allows you to only return data after meeting certain thresholds for aggregation. Effective, you typically use the aggregating function you have from SELECT (e.g., SUM(total_investment_dollars)) then impose the condition you want to meet via HAVING (e.g., SUM(total_investment_dollars) >= 10000000000).

sql_query <- "
SELECT state_name, SUM(total_investment_dollars) 
FROM investment.ruraldevelopment
GROUP BY state_name 
HAVING SUM(total_investment_dollars) >= 10000000000
"

dbGetQuery(connection, sql_query)
       state_name         sum
1  North Carolina 19625458505
2         Florida 13333056773
3       Louisiana 13359196375
4  South Carolina 12042742339
5        Missouri 13379011326
6         Indiana 10344087246
7        Michigan 11861916179
8    Pennsylvania 10431877304
9        Kentucky 12080928014
10       Virginia 17451945311
11        Georgia 17317886258
12     California 12541703806
13      Tennessee 13819292794
14          Texas 15995187413
15        Alabama 10205762054
sql_query <- "
with temp_table as (
  SELECT state_name, SUM(total_investment_dollars) as total
  FROM investment.ruraldevelopment
  GROUP BY state_name 
)

select *
from temp_table
where total > 10000000000
"

dbGetQuery(connection, sql_query)
       state_name       total
1  North Carolina 19625458505
2         Florida 13333056773
3       Louisiana 13359196375
4  South Carolina 12042742339
5        Missouri 13379011326
6         Indiana 10344087246
7        Michigan 11861916179
8    Pennsylvania 10431877304
9        Kentucky 12080928014
10       Virginia 17451945311
11        Georgia 17317886258
12     California 12541703806
13      Tennessee 13819292794
14          Texas 15995187413
15        Alabama 10205762054

This is now the inherent order of the SQL scripts:

SELECT > FROM > WHERE > GROUP BY > HAVING > ORDER BY
